"{\"paper\": {\"status\": \"map_fixed\", \"title\": \"CCG Syntactic Reordering Models for Phrase-based Machine Translation\", \"url\": \"http://www.aclweb.org/anthology/W12-3126\", \"abstract\": \"Statistical phrase-based machine translation requires no linguistic information beyond word-aligned parallel corpora (Zens et al., 2002; Koehn et al., 2003). Unfortunately, this linguistic agnosticism often produces ungrammatical translations. Syntax, or sentence structure, could provide guidance to phrase-based systems, but the \\u201cnon-constituent\\u201d word strings that phrase-based decoders manipulate complicate the use of most recursive syntactic tools. We address these issues by using Combinatory Categorial Grammar, or CCG, (Steedman, 2000), which has a much more flexible notion of constituency, thereby providing more labels for putative non-constituent multi-word  translation phrases. Using CCG parse charts, we train a syntactic analogue of a lexicalized reordering model by labeling phrase table entries with multi-word labels and demonstrate significant improvements in translating between  Urdu and English, two language pairs with divergent sentence structure.\", \"field\": \"Machine Translation\", \"user\": \"MT-admin_Eunsol_Choi\"}, \"map_name\": \"CCG_Syntactic_Reorde_1.html\", \"_id\": {\"$oid\": \"5858b889dc9e6c4509cf039a\"}, \"annotation\": {\"metrics\": [{\"type\": \"Quantitative\", \"name\": \"Statistical phrase-based machine translation (PMT)_BLEU-4\", \"task_name\": {\"name\": \"Statistical phrase-based machine translation (PMT)\"}, \"measure\": \"BLEU-4\"}, {\"type\": \"Qualitative\", \"name\": \"Statistical phrase-based machine translation (PMT)_quality\", \"task_name\": {\"name\": \"Statistical phrase-based machine translation (PMT)\"}, \"measure\": \"quality\"}, {\"type\": \"Quantitative\", \"name\": \"Statistical phrase-based machine translation (PMT)_BLEU\", \"task_name\": {\"name\": \"Statistical phrase-based machine translation (PMT)\"}, \"measu